data.name: lblIntroduction.Text
data.value:
Welcome to the Random Item Giver Updater Legacy Help Documentation!
This documentation contains (hopefully) everything you need to know when using this application. It's designed to help users that aren't very tech-savvy and maybe also people who already know how things work.
The images and explanations in this documentation are always up-to-date to the version you're running so you can get the newest information. Each page also shows the 'last edited' date so you can check if it's actually updated. If you find any mistakes, please don't hesitate to let me know!
Use the tabs above to switch between pages. Each page contains information on a specific topic and is illustrated with pictures to further help understanding the content. Some pages are for more advanced users, those are marked with '(advanced)'. The tab 'other' contains everything else that's off-topic or just some small information that isn't worth its own page.
You may also find links at the bottom of pages. These links sometimes open other help pages, sometimes they show small explanations for words or open help pages, there's a bunch of things these can do.
In case this documentation doesn't solve issues you might be experiencing or you still need further help you can always contact me on discord.

data.name: lblSimpleOverview.Text
data.value:
This software helps you add items to the Random Item Giver Datapack (see download link below). It also comes with other neat features focused around the datapack. Please note that the datapack only works for the Java Edition of Minecraft.
In the Main window you can add items to the Random Item Giver Datapack and access all the other features. It has an easy mode and an advanced mode so everyone can easily utilize it! It also allows you to save and open schemes and profiles which make using the software much easier.
The Duplicate Finder can check loot tables in the Random Item Giver Datapack for duplicate items. It will then list those along with the loot table they're in.
The Output log is a feature for more advanced users and helps debugging the software. It lists actions made in the software and shows error messages that may occur. It also possible to export this log.
The Settings window allows you to manage your preferences in the software, like editing profiles, selecting default settings, enabling specific warnings or resetting the software completely.
The Changelog and About window contain information about updates and general information about the software.

data.name: lblDescriptionAddItemsBasic.Text
data.value:
When adding new items, the first thing you're gonna do is select the datapack folder and the datapack version.
After that, in the textbox you write all the IDs of the items you want to add. In case you want to add a potion or enchanted book, you can also add a NBT tag.
On the right side, you can specify the types of the items you want to add. You select wether the items are creative-only items or not, and if they are, you can select the type. You can also save and load schemes.
On the bottom, you can find the option to disable Advanced View and also an option to add items the 'fast way'.
After you've specified all your settings, you can hit 'Add item to datapack' to begin the process. There is also a small output text box which shows you if the process has been completed.

data.name: lblDescriptionAddingItemsAdvanced.Text
data.value:
When adding new items, the first thing you're gonna do is select the datapack folder and the datapack version.
After that, in the textbox you write all the IDs of the items you want to add. When 'use the same prefix for all items' is disabled, (when adding modded items for example) you will also need to include the prefix, otherwise you don't. In case you want to add a potion or enchanted book, you can also add a NBT tag.
On the right side, you can specify the types of the items you want to add. You select wether the items are creative-only items or not, and if they are, you can select the type. There is also a plenty of other options to choose from, which will add the items to different loot tables. You can also save and load schemes.
On the bottom, you can find the option to disable Advanced View and also an option to add items the 'fast way'.
After you've specified all your settings, you can hit 'Add item to datapack' to begin the process. There is also a small output text box which shows you if the process has been completed.

data.name: lblDescriptionDuplicateFinder.Text
data.value:
The duplicate finder can help you detect, wether an item exits in the datapack multiple times.
It's pretty simple: You select the datapack, hit "Check datapack" and after loading for a bit it will show a list of all duplicates that were found, and also which loot table the originate from.
After that, you will need to manually open up the loot tables and remove the duplicates.

data.name: lblDescriptionSchemes.Text
data.value:
Profiles and Schemes allow you to quickly save information so you can access it later on. It also gets saved if you restart or even reinstall the software.
Profiles are used to save a datapack path and its corresponding version. The datapack path can be any valid file path, while the version needs to be selected from a list. The settings menu features an option to automatically load a profile when starting the application. There you can also find the profile manager, which allows you to edit profiles without loading them into the main window.
Schemes on the other hand save information about specific item groups. It holds information like the item type (Potion, Enchanted Book, etc...) as well as the NBT Tag and Prefix. This is useful if you're adding different kinds of items. You won't have to tick each checkbox over and over and enter the prefix 20 different times. You can just load the scheme! As with the Profiles, you will find an option to load a default scheme in the settings menu. Schemes don't have their own editor, you will need to edit them through the main menu. There are also a handfull of default schemes which can be restored through the settings menu, if necessary.

data.name: lblOther.Text
data.value:
The Item List Importer allows you to select a file, that contains a list of items. You can use a list that contains prefixes or no prefixes, but not a mix. Depending on this, you will also need to select the correct option in the main menu. It's recommended to use some kind of mod to generate that list. For Forge, I recommend using the TellMe Mod. If your list contains vanilla items, you can also select to not import them, which is recommended, since the datapack usually already contains those.
The output log contains detailed information about what happens in the software. This can be really useful if you need to debug the software or just want to know what exactly is going on. The colors help you to differentiate the different types of messages, which are INFO, WARNING and ERROR. You can also save the log as a text file, if you wish to.
If you want to visit the Github page of this software, here you go:
You may also like to visit the websites where the Random Item Giver is hosted:
Also, I wanna say thanks to Phoenix SC who originally made the datapack! I asked him if I could continue updating the datapack and he gave me permission! Without him, all of this wouldn't have existed in the first place. Additionally, I need to give credit to the many different people who contributed to the datapack in some way. You can find them in the CREDITS.txt file in the Random Item Giver Datapack.
If you need further help, want to report a bug, or have any other issue, you an always join my discord server!
Lastly, please note that this software has entered legacy state and was replaced by a newer, more stable version which you can find here. While this version will still be maintained for a bit, it will no longer receive major content updates or support for newer MC versions. It is recommended to switch to the new software as soon as possible.
